# Axon Phase 2 - Media Integration Specification

## Goal

Phase 2 extends the local Sender/Receiver bridge with bidirectional media synchronization.

The Sender tracks the currently active Android media session and sends playback metadata to the Receiver. The Receiver reconstructs that state as a local shadow media experience so the Receiver phone and its connected watch can display the current track and send transport commands back to the Sender.

Security is still intentionally out of scope for this phase.

## Roles

- Sender: the Android phone that owns the real media playback session.
- Receiver: the Android phone that receives media updates, displays the mirrored media state, exposes media controls, and forwards commands back to the Sender.
- Watch: a device connected to the Receiver through Android's normal notification/media-session pipeline or through a companion app.

## Functional Requirements

### Media Mirroring

The Sender must:

- Monitor active Android media sessions.
- Pick the highest-priority playable session, preferring sessions whose playback state is `STATE_PLAYING`.
- Extract title, artist, album, duration, position, playback speed, playing state, package name, and artwork.
- Send media updates only when meaningful state changes occur.
- Send a media-clear event when playback disappears or the active session is destroyed.

The Receiver must:

- Store the latest active media payload in app state.
- Render a media panel in the app.
- Show a media-style notification.
- Maintain a shadow media session that the Android system and connected watch can discover.
- Keep artwork available in both the app UI and the media notification.

### Remote Commands

The Receiver must translate local UI, notification, watch, and media-session controls into protocol commands:

- `PLAY`
- `PAUSE`
- `SKIP_TO_NEXT`
- `SKIP_TO_PREVIOUS`

The Sender must dispatch those commands to the real active media session through `MediaController.TransportControls`.

## Protocol Messages

### `MEDIA_UPDATE`

```json
{
  "type": "MEDIA_UPDATE",
  "media": {
    "title": "String",
    "artist": "String",
    "album": "String",
    "duration": 0,
    "position": 0,
    "playbackSpeed": 1.0,
    "isPlaying": true,
    "lastPositionUpdateTime": 0,
    "packageName": "String",
    "artworkBase64": "Base64 JPEG or null"
  }
}
```

### `MEDIA_COMMAND`

```json
{
  "type": "MEDIA_COMMAND",
  "command": {
    "action": "PLAY | PAUSE | SKIP_TO_NEXT | SKIP_TO_PREVIOUS"
  }
}
```

### `MEDIA_CLEAR`

```json
{
  "type": "MEDIA_CLEAR"
}
```

## Sender Implementation

The Sender uses `MediaSessionManager` and `MediaController.Callback`.

Implementation file:

- `app/src/main/java/com/axon/bridge/data/MediaSessionTracker.kt`

Main behavior:

- Registers `MediaSessionManager.OnActiveSessionsChangedListener`.
- Uses the notification listener component when calling `getActiveSessions`.
- Selects a playing session first, then falls back to the first available session.
- Registers a callback on the selected `MediaController`.
- Publishes updates when metadata or playback state changes.
- Encodes artwork as a bounded JPEG payload before transport.
- Dispatches received commands through `transportControls`.

## Receiver Implementation

### Shadow Media Session

The Receiver uses `MediaSessionCompat`, not only framework `MediaSession`.

Implementation file:

- `app/src/main/java/com/axon/bridge/data/ShadowMediaSession.kt`

Reason:

- Some watch companion stacks query compat media sessions using commands such as `android.support.v4.media.session.command.GET_EXTRA_BINDER`.
- A plain framework `MediaSession` can show metadata on the watch but may not expose the compat binder path that the watch expects for controls.

Main behavior:

- Creates a `MediaSessionCompat` tagged `AxonShadowMediaSession`.
- Sets callbacks for play, pause, next, previous, and media-button events.
- Publishes Axon `MediaCommandPayload` values into the command bus.
- Updates metadata and playback state from incoming `MediaPayload`.
- Keeps the session active while media is available.
- Links the session token to the media-style notification.

### Silent Playback Anchor

Implementation file:

- `app/src/main/java/com/axon/bridge/data/SilentPlaybackAnchor.kt`

Reason:

- Some watches show a shadow media session but do not route play/pause/next/previous to it unless the Receiver is also perceived by Android as an active media playback source.
- The Receiver is not playing real user audio, so Axon starts a zero-volume `AudioTrack` while mirrored media is active.

Behavior:

- Creates a stream-mode mono PCM `AudioTrack`.
- Uses media audio attributes.
- Sets volume to `0f`.
- Continuously writes silence while shadow media is active.
- Stops and releases the track when media is cleared or the bridge stops.

This was the final fix that made watch controls route back into Axon's Receiver-side media session.

### Media Notification

Implementation file:

- `app/src/main/java/com/axon/bridge/service/MediaNotificationManager.kt`

Main behavior:

- Uses `NotificationCompat.Builder`.
- Uses `androidx.media.app.NotificationCompat.MediaStyle`.
- Attaches the `MediaSessionCompat.Token`.
- Shows previous, play/pause, and next actions.
- Builds notification actions through media-button pending intents so notification/watch controls enter the media-session path.
- Shows artwork as the notification large icon.

### Media Button Receiver

Implementation file:

- `app/src/main/java/com/axon/bridge/service/AxonMediaButtonReceiver.kt`

Main behavior:

- Receives `android.intent.action.MEDIA_BUTTON`.
- First routes the intent into the active `MediaSessionCompat` through `MediaButtonReceiver.handleIntent`.
- Falls back to manual `KeyEvent` parsing if no active compat session exists.

Manifest entry:

```xml
<receiver
    android:name=".service.AxonMediaButtonReceiver"
    android:exported="true">
    <intent-filter>
        <action android:name="android.intent.action.MEDIA_BUTTON" />
    </intent-filter>
</receiver>
```

## Transport Integration

Implementation file:

- `app/src/main/java/com/axon/bridge/data/BridgeTransport.kt`

Main behavior:

- Sender sends `MEDIA_UPDATE` and `MEDIA_CLEAR`.
- Receiver sends `MEDIA_COMMAND`.
- Both directions reuse the existing WebSocket connection.
- Media commands are collected from `MediaBridgeBus.commands`.

## Important Diagnostics

Expected useful logs:

- `Media tracker starting`
- `Media session selected: <package>`
- `Media state: <title> (playing)`
- `Sent media: <title>`
- `Media update received: <title>`
- `Shadow media session ready`
- `Shadow media updated: <title>`
- `Shadow media audio focus: granted`
- `Silent media anchor started`
- `Shadow media command: Pause`
- `Sent media command: Pause`
- `Media command received: Pause`
- `Media command dispatched: Pause`

If the watch shows the track but no command logs appear, inspect whether the Receiver is actually exposing an active media session and whether the silent playback anchor started.

